{"title_page": "Laxmi Chhaya", "text_new": "[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jF5uaqjySqQ Laxmi Chhya dancing in Gumnaam (1965) , used also in Ghost World (2001)]{{Use Australian English|date=April 2019}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Laxmi Chhaya\n| image              = [[File:Laxmi Chhaya in Teesri Manzil.jpg|thumb|Laxmi Chhaya in Bollywood movie Teesri Manzil]]\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Laxmi Chhaya in [[Baharon Ke Sapne]]\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1948|01|7}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2004|05|09|1948|01|07}}\n| death_place        = [[Mumbai, India]]\n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| occupation         = Actress, Dancer, Dance Teacher\n| years_active       = 1958-1982 (Actress)\n}}\n'''Laxmi Chhaya''' (7 January 1948 \u2013 9 May 2004) was an Indian actress and dancer who appeared in [[Bollywood]] and [[Marathi language|Marathi]] films. She was cast in over 100 films, with her career spanning over 20 years. She was active in films between 1958-1982.\n\n== Career ==\nChhaya began acting with a guest appearance in [[Talaq (1958 film)|''Talaq'']] (1958). In 1962, Chhaya starred in the film [[Naughty Boy (film)|''Naughty Boy'']] as Bela, her first role that wasn't a guest role. \n\nIn 1965, she made a guest appearance in ''[[Gumnaam]]'', as the masked dancer in the song [[Jaan Pehechan Ho]]. Parts of her performance were included in the opening credits of the U.S. film [[Ghost World (film)|''Ghost World'']] (2001).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://madhulikaliddle.com/2011/06/17/gumnaam-1965/|title=Gumnaam (1965)|last=dustedoff|date=2011-06-17|website=Dustedoff|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Chhaya starred as Meena in ''[[Teesri Manzil]]'' (1966).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uiowa.edu/indiancinema/teesri-manzil|title=Teesri Manzil {{!}} Indian Cinema|website=uiowa.edu|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Throughout the following year, Chhaya had begun to make more guest appearances, and appeared in ''[[Ram Aur Shyam]]'' (1967), ''[[Baharon Ke Sapne]]'' (1967), ''[[Upkar]]'' (1967), and ''[[Raat Aur Din]]'' (1967).\n\nIn 1968, Chhaya starred in [[Duniya (1968 film)|''Duniya'']] as Laxmi, a role named after her. She next starred as Rita in the film ''[[Aya Sawan Jhoom Ke]]'' (1969). She also starred in the film ''[[Pyar Ka Mausam]]'' (1969). In 1971, Chhaya starred as Munni in ''[[Mera Gaon Mera Desh]]'', her first role as part of the main cast. She starred as Tanu Thakur in [[Raaste Kaa Patthar]] (1972), and starred in the film ''[[Do Chor]]'' in the same year. \n\nChhaya retired the film industry in 1986. In the years prior to her death, Chhaya went on to open her own dance school, where she taught dancing to indigent children.\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n\n*''[[Talaq (1958 film)|Talaq]] (1958)''\n*''[[Bada Aadmi]] (1961)''\n*''[[Royal Mail (1963 film)|Royal Mail]] (1963)''\n*''[[Bluff Master (1963 film)|Bluff Master]] (1963)''\n*''[[Gumnaam]] (1965)''\n*''[[Teesri Manzil]] (1966)''\n*''[[Ram Aur Shyam]] (1967)''\n*''[[Raaz (1967 film)|Raaz]] (1967)''\n*''[[Baharon Ke Sapne]] (1967)''\n*''[[Izzat (1968 film)|Izzat]] (1968)''\n*''[[Aya Sawan Jhoom Ke]] (1969)''\n*''[[Mere Humsafar]] (1970)''\n*''[[Mera Gaon Mera Desh]] (1971)''\n*''Kundan (1972)''\n*''[[Tanhai (film)|Tanhai]] (1972)''\n*''[[Bindiya Aur Bandook]] (1973)''\n*''Suraj Aur Chanda (1973)''\n*''Parakh (1981)''\n\n== Death ==\nOn May 9, 2004, Chhaya died from [[cancer]] in [[Mumbai]] at the age of 56.<ref name=\"bulletin22\">Listener's Bulletin No. 125, September 2004, p 4.</ref><ref name=\"screen india22\">[http://syndication.screenindia.com/news/tatas-finally-pull-plug-on-bangla-projects/8277/ Laxmi Chhaya & Dilawar Khan] ScreenIndia.com 4 June 2004 {{dead link|date=June 2013}}</ref> Tributes have been published and created in recognition of Chhaya's work in film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/articles/2019/may/9/20549|title=5 unforgettable songs filmed on Laxmi Chhaya|last=Pandya|first=Sonal|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://memsaabstory.com/2009/04/29/my-ten-favorite-laxmi-chhaya-songs/|title=My ten favorite Laxmi Chhaya songs|date=2009-04-29|website=MemsaabStory|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0156857}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chhaya, Laxmi}}\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Indian female dancers]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Marathi cinema]]\n[[Category:Dancers from Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Women artists from Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dancers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=April 2019}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Laxmi Chhaya\n| image              = [[File:Laxmi Chhaya in Teesri Manzil.jpg|thumb|Laxmi Chhaya in Bollywood movie Teesri Manzil]]\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Laxmi Chhaya in [[Baharon Ke Sapne]]\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1948|01|7}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2004|05|09|1948|01|07}}\n| death_place        = [[Mumbai, India]]\n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| occupation         = Actress, Dancer, Dance Teacher\n| years_active       = 1958-1982 (Actress)\n}}\n'''Laxmi Chhaya''' (7 January 1948 \u2013 9 May 2004) was an Indian actress and dancer who appeared in [[Bollywood]] and [[Marathi language|Marathi]] films. She was cast in over 100 films, with her career spanning over 20 years. She was active in films between 1958-1982.\n\n== Career ==\nChhaya began acting with a guest appearance in [[Talaq (1958 film)|''Talaq'']] (1958). In 1962, Chhaya starred in the film [[Naughty Boy (film)|''Naughty Boy'']] as Bela, her first role that wasn't a guest role. \n\nIn 1965, she made a guest appearance in ''[[Gumnaam]]'', as the masked dancer in the song [[Jaan Pehechan Ho]]. Parts of her performance were included in the opening credits of the U.S. film [[Ghost World (film)|''Ghost World'']] (2001).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://madhulikaliddle.com/2011/06/17/gumnaam-1965/|title=Gumnaam (1965)|last=dustedoff|date=2011-06-17|website=Dustedoff|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Chhaya starred as Meena in ''[[Teesri Manzil]]'' (1966).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uiowa.edu/indiancinema/teesri-manzil|title=Teesri Manzil {{!}} Indian Cinema|website=uiowa.edu|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Throughout the following year, Chhaya had begun to make more guest appearances, and appeared in ''[[Ram Aur Shyam]]'' (1967), ''[[Baharon Ke Sapne]]'' (1967), ''[[Upkar]]'' (1967), and ''[[Raat Aur Din]]'' (1967).\n\nIn 1968, Chhaya starred in [[Duniya (1968 film)|''Duniya'']] as Laxmi, a role named after her. She next starred as Rita in the film ''[[Aya Sawan Jhoom Ke]]'' (1969). She also starred in the film ''[[Pyar Ka Mausam]]'' (1969). In 1971, Chhaya starred as Munni in ''[[Mera Gaon Mera Desh]]'', her first role as part of the main cast. She starred as Tanu Thakur in [[Raaste Kaa Patthar]] (1972), and starred in the film ''[[Do Chor]]'' in the same year. \n\nChhaya retired the film industry in 1986. In the years prior to her death, Chhaya went on to open her own dance school, where she taught dancing to indigent children.\n\n== Selected filmography ==\n\n*''[[Talaq (1958 film)|Talaq]] (1958)''\n*''[[Bada Aadmi]] (1961)''\n*''[[Royal Mail (1963 film)|Royal Mail]] (1963)''\n*''[[Bluff Master (1963 film)|Bluff Master]] (1963)''\n*''[[Gumnaam]] (1965)''\n*''[[Teesri Manzil]] (1966)''\n*''[[Ram Aur Shyam]] (1967)''\n*''[[Raaz (1967 film)|Raaz]] (1967)''\n*''[[Baharon Ke Sapne]] (1967)''\n*''[[Izzat (1968 film)|Izzat]] (1968)''\n*''[[Aya Sawan Jhoom Ke]] (1969)''\n*''[[Mere Humsafar]] (1970)''\n*''[[Mera Gaon Mera Desh]] (1971)''\n*''Kundan (1972)''\n*''[[Tanhai (film)|Tanhai]] (1972)''\n*''[[Bindiya Aur Bandook]] (1973)''\n*''Suraj Aur Chanda (1973)''\n*''Parakh (1981)''\n\n== Death ==\nOn May 9, 2004, Chhaya died from [[cancer]] in [[Mumbai]] at the age of 56.<ref name=\"bulletin22\">Listener's Bulletin No. 125, September 2004, p 4.</ref><ref name=\"screen india22\">[http://syndication.screenindia.com/news/tatas-finally-pull-plug-on-bangla-projects/8277/ Laxmi Chhaya & Dilawar Khan] ScreenIndia.com 4 June 2004 {{dead link|date=June 2013}}</ref> Tributes have been published and created in recognition of Chhaya's work in film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/articles/2019/may/9/20549|title=5 unforgettable songs filmed on Laxmi Chhaya|last=Pandya|first=Sonal|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://memsaabstory.com/2009/04/29/my-ten-favorite-laxmi-chhaya-songs/|title=My ten favorite Laxmi Chhaya songs|date=2009-04-29|website=MemsaabStory|language=en|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0156857}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chhaya, Laxmi}}\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Indian female dancers]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Marathi cinema]]\n[[Category:Dancers from Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Women artists from Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian dancers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n", "name_user":