in [[Gunnison County, Colorado|Gunnison County]], [[Colorado]], [[United States]].<ref name=NAVD88/><ref name=PB/><ref name=GNIS/>  Gothic Mountain takes its name from its pinnacles said to resemble [[Gothic architecture]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=Govt. Print. Off. | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n139 140]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Geology|Geography|North America|United States|Colorado|Mountains}}\n*[[List of mountain ranges of Colorado|List of Colorado mountain ranges]]\n*[[List of mountains of the United States#Colorado|List of Colorado mountain summits]]\n**[[List of Colorado fourteeners]]\n**[[List of mountain peaks of Colorado#Highest major summits|List of Colorado 4000 meter prominent summits]]\n**[[List of the most prominent summits of Colorado]]\n*[[List of Colorado county high points]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister project links}}\n\n{{Mountains of Colorado}}\n{{Colorado}}\n{{Protected areas of Colorado}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Colorado]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Gunnison County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Gunnison National Forest]]\n[[Category:North American 3000 m summits]]\n\n{{Colorado-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Gothic Mountains|Gothic Peak}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Gothic Mountain\n| other_name = \n| photo = Mount Gothic.jpg\n| photo_alt = Gothic Mountain\n| photo_caption = A view of the Gothic Mountain from [[Crested Butte]] in 2010.\n| elevation_ft = 12631\n| elevation_ref = <ref name=NAVD88>The elevation of Gothic Mountain includes an adjustment of +1.936&nbsp;m (+6.35&nbsp;ft) from [[Sea Level Datum of 1929|NGVD&nbsp;29]] to [[North American Vertical Datum of 1988|NAVD&nbsp;88]].</ref><ref name=PB>{{cite peakbagger|pid=16644|title=Gothic Mountain, Colorado|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| prominence_ft = 1645\n| prominence_ref = <ref name=PB/>\n| isolation_mi = 2.73\n| isolation_ref = <ref name=PB/>\n| listing = [[Colorado prominent summits]]\n| range = [[Elk Mountains]]<ref name=PB/>\n| parent_peak = \n| location = [[Gunnison County, Colorado|Gunnison County]], [[Colorado]], [[United States|U.S.]]<ref name=GNIS/>\n| map = Colorado\n| map_caption = '''[[Colorado]]'''\n| coordinates = {{coord|38.9563802|N|107.0106015|W|type:mountain_region:US-CO_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates_ref = <ref name=GNIS>{{cite gnis|id=186479|name=Gothic Mountain|accessdate=October 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey#Topographic mapping|USGS 7.5' topographic map]]<br/>Oh-be-joyful, Colorado<ref name=GNIS/>\n| type = \n| volcanic_arc/belt= \n| age = \n| last_eruption = \n| first_ascent =\n| easiest_route =\n}}\n\n'''Gothic Mountain''' is a [[Topographic prominence|prominent]] [[mountain]] [[summit]] in the [[Elk Mountains (Colorado)|Elk Mountains]] range of the [[Rocky Mountains]] of [[North America]].  The {{convert|12631|ft|0|adj=on}} peak is located in [[Gunnison National Forest]], {{convert|1.8|km|order=flip}} west by south ([[Absolute bearing|bearing]] 260\u00b0) of the [[ghost town]] of [[Gothic, Colorado|Gothic]] in [[Gunnison County, Colorado|Gunnison County]], [[Colorado]], [[United States]].<ref name=NAVD88/><ref name=PB/><ref name=GNIS/>  Gothic Mountain takes its name from its pinnacles said to resemble [[Gothic architecture]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=Govt. Print. Off. | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n139 140]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Geology|Geography|North America|United States|Colorado|Mountains}}\n*[[List of mountain ranges of Colorado|List of Colorado mountain ranges]]\n*[[List of mountains of the United States#Colorado|List of Colorado mountain summits]]\n**[[List of Colorado fourteeners]]\n**[[List of mountain peaks of Colorado#Highest major summits|List of Colorado 4000 meter prominent summits]]\n**[[List of the most prominent summits of Colorado]]\n*[[List of Colorado county high points]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister project links}}\n\n{{Mountains of Colorado}}\n{{Colorado}}\n{{Protected areas of Colorado}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Colorado]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Gunnison County, Colorado]]\n[[Category:Gunnison National Forest]]\n[[Category:North American 3000 m summits]]\n\n{{Colorado-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zapus", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gothic_Mountain"}
{"title_page": "Fern G. Z. Carr", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Fern G. Z. Carr\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = File:Fern G Z Carr.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1956}}\n| birth_place      = [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Poet, translator, teacher, lawyer\n| language         = English, French, Spanish, Yiddish, Italian, Mandarin\n| residence        = \n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = [[University of Manitoba]];<br>[[Coll\u00e8ge Universitaire de Saint-Boniface]]\n| home_town        = \n| period           = 1978 - present\n| genre            = Poetry\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = Shards of Crystal; I Am\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = Going to Mars with MAVEN; Poem of the Month for Canada\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = {{url|ferngzcarr.com}}\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n\n'''Fern G. Z. Carr''' is a contemporary Canadian poet who resides in [[Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]]. A full member of the League of Canadian Poets and the Federation of BC Writers, Fern G. Z. Carr is the author of ''Shards of Crystal'' (Silver Bow Publishing, 2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.ca/dp/1927616964/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1542292047&sr=8-1&keywords=Shards+of+Crystal+Fern+G.+Z.+Carr|title=Shards of Crystal: Amazon.ca: Fern G. Z. Carr: Books|website=Amazon.ca|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref> Carr is a former lawyer, teacher, and past president of both the Kelowna branch of the BC Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals ([[SPCA]]) and Project Literacy Central Okanagan Society. She composes and translates poetry in six languages including Mandarin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ferngzcarr.com/|title=Fern G. Z. Carr|website=Ferngzcarr.com|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref> She has been published in poetry anthologies, journals, and magazines multiple times in thirty-four countries. One of her poems is currently orbiting the planet [[Mars]] aboard NASA's MAVEN spacecraft. <ref>http://lasp.colorado.edu/home/maven/2013/07/15/public-voting-opens-on-maven-haiku-contest. Retrieved on May 22, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Personal life and education==\nFern G. Z. Carr was born in 1956 in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]]. Carr attended the [[University of Manitoba]] where she obtained her Bachelor of Arts degree (BA) and her Bachelor of Laws degree (LLB). She received her Call to the Bar from the [[Law Society of Manitoba]]. After briefly practising law, Carr decided to pursue her interest in languages. She enrolled at le Coll\u00e8ge Universitaire de Saint-Boniface where she received her Certificat en \u00c9ducation and was the recipient of the Manitoba Government Book Prize for highest standing in her program.<ref>{{cite book |title=The University of Manitoba 104th Annual Convocation |date=1983}}</ref> She subsequently taught French Immersion before moving to [[Kelowna]] with her family in 1999. She is married and is the sister-in-law of [[James Gordon Carr]], Member of Parliament.\n\n==Writing style and influences==\nCarr's early poetry from the late 1970s to the mid-1990s is more representative of traditional meter and rhyme. She subsequently began to experiment with different forms and styles while continuing to compose traditional poetry in set forms such as [[pantoum]] and [[ghazal]]. An admirer of [[Emily Dickinson]], Carr liked the use of [[em dashes]] and often incorporated them into her poems. In the 2000s, Carr's poetry style became more eclectic as she experimented with design. This was particularly evident in her [[Visual poetry|visual]] and [[concrete poetry]] as well as in her experimental math / science poems such as \"The Fickle Nature of the Parabola\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carr |first1=Fern G. Z. |title=The Fickle Nature of the Parabola |journal=Windsor Review |date=Fall 2018 |volume=43 |issue=2 |page=128}}</ref> and \"Holocaust Genealogy\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carr |first1=Fern G. Z. |title=Holocaust Genealogy |journal=mgversion2 |date=July 2016 |volume=85 |page=84}}</ref> To date, her stylistic focus is [[free verse]].\n\nWhile Carr's poetry primarily is written in English, she also composes poems in [[French language|French]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Yiddish]] and the [[Chinese Mandarin]] dialect. Even though she occasionally translates the works of other poets, she tends to focus on bilingual and trilingual side-by-side translations of her own poetry.\n\nMany of Carr's poems were influenced by her early years in Winnipeg's West End where she bore witness to poverty and crime. While this darkness is evident in some of her poetry, she also composes poems which evoke a diverse array of human emotions.\n\n==''Shards of Crystal''==\n''Shards of Crystal'' reflects a dichotomy and as such, is described as a metamorphosis of darkness to light. Dealing with issues such as suicide, trauma, dementia, cruelty to animals, and the death of a child, the book then gradually changes course. It begins its transformative move towards the beauty of life with poems about musicality, spiritual liberation and the philosophy of existence. It culminates in a philosophical examination of mankind's place in the universe with Carr's signature poem, \"I Am\".<ref name=\"parl.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://bdp.parl.ca/About/Parliament/Poet/poem-selected-former-poet-laureate2-e.html?id=1&id4=254|title=The Parliamentary Poet Laureate|website=Bdp.parl.ca|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe imagery in ''Shards of Crystal'' parallels the darkness-to-light chronology of Carr's poems. This transition is essentially a redemptive move both literally and metaphorically, reconciling the pain of \"Shards\" at the outset of the book with the beauty and enlightenment of \"Crystal\" at the conclusion. Beginning with the darkness of night and becoming progressively lighter, her poems ultimately achieve the illumination of the eternal. This is in keeping with the overarching theme of hope as expressed by the Victor Hugo quote at the start of the book: \"Even the darkest night will end and the sun will rise.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hugo |first1=Victor |title=Les Mis\u00e9rables |date=1987 |publisher=Signet Classics |isbn=9780451525260 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lesmisrablessign00vict }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nCarr has been published extensively worldwide in Australia, Austria, Canada, China, Cyprus, Finland, France, Holland, India, Ireland, Israel, Italy, Malawi, Mauritius, Mayotte Island, Mexico, Morocco, Nepal, New Zealand, Nigeria, Peru, Philippines, Romania, Seychelles, Singapore, South Africa, Spain, Sweden, Thailand, United Arab Emirates, United Kingdom (in England, Scotland and Wales) and USA.\n\nAdditionally, she has written literary non-fiction articles which have been published in the Federation of BC Writers ''WordWorks Magazine'' (2020) and ''Part of the Discourse: An Interdisciplinary Humanities Journal'' (2019).\n\n===Books===\n*''Shards of Crystal'' (Silver Bow Publishing, 2018) {{ISBN|978-1-927616-96-3}}\n\n===Selected anthologies===\n*''Dreamscapes'' - 2019\n*''Lost and Found'' - 2019\n*''Celestial Musings'' - 2018\n*''Climate of Opinion'' - 2017\n*''Nuclear Impact: Broken Atoms in Our Hands'' - 2017\n*''Fire and Sky'' - 2016\n*''Memory and Loss'' - 2016\n*''Childhood Regained'' - 2016\n*''Amsterdam Quarterly 2015 Yearbook'' - 2015\n*''Contemporary Poetry - An Anthology of Present Day Best Poems'' Vol. 2 - 2015\n*''Love Where the Nights are Twice as Long'' - 2015\n*''A Quiet Shelter There'' - 2015\n*''Storm Cycle 2013 - The Best of Kind of a Hurricane Press'' - 2014\n*''The Body Electric'' - 2013\n*''Voices Israel'' - 2012\n*''Sol: English Writing in Mexico'' - 2012\n*''Butterfly Away'' - 2011\n*''Van Gogh's Ear'' 7 - 2010\n\n===Selected journals===\n*''The Laurel Review'' 51.2 - 2018\n*''The London Reader'' - Autumn, 2017\n*''The Caf\u00e9 Review'' 27 - Winter, 2016\n*''Slant'' - Summer, 2015\n*''Pasque Petals'' - Fall 2015\n*''Whole Terrain'' 21 - 2014\n*''Zona de Carga'' No. 6 - August 2014\n*''MaLa - The Chengdu Bookworm Literary Journal'' 3 - June 2013\n*''Legal Studies Forum'' XXXVII, No. 1 - 2013\n*''phati'tude Literary Magazine'' 3, No. 3 - Fall 2011\n*''The Toronto Quarterly'' 8 - Nov. 2011\n*''White Wall Review'' 135 - 2011\n*''new contrast South African Literary Journal'' 38.4, No. 152 - Summer 2010\n*''The Nashwaak Review'' 24-25, No. 1 - Summer/Fall 2010\n*''Prairie Fire'' 31, No. 3 - Fall 2010\n*''Poetry New Zealand'' 41 - September 2010\n*''Windsor Review'' 42, No. - 2009\n\n==Selected awards and honours==\n*Haiku included on the Going to Mars Contest DVD aboard NASA's MAVEN spacecraft to the planet Mars<ref>http://lasp.colorado.edu/home/maven/2013/07/15/public-voting-opens-on-maven-haiku-contest/. Retrieved on May 22, 2019.</ref>\n*2013 Pushcart Prize Nominee - ''The Worcester Review''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theworcesterreview.org/2013/11/pushcart-nominees.html|title=Pushcart Nominees|first=Diane Vanaskie|last=Mulligan|website=Theworcesterreview.org|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n*A winner of Il Premio Nazionale di Letteratura \"Il Meleteo di Guido Gozzano\" 4\u00b0 Edizione (Sezione Autori di Lingua Straniera)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amicidiguidogozzano.jimdo.com/2014-bando-concorso-e-premiazione/poems-2014/|title=Poems 2014 by country (selected by the judges)|website=Benvenuti su amicidiguidogozzano!|accessdate=25 December 2018}}</ref>\n*Poem, \"I Am\", selected by the Parliamentary Poet Laureate of Canada as Poem of the Month for Canada, May 2010<ref name=\"parl.ca\"/>\n*Featured solo guest presenter at the Rotary Centre for the Arts Mary Irwin Theatre in conjunction with Culture Days and the Kelowna Arts and Culture Festival 2019 <ref>https://www.kelownadailycourier.ca/calendar/event_fc8e2048-bae3-11e9-a845-5cb9017beffc.html. Retrieved on 6 October 2019.</ref>\n*Biographical listing in ''The World's Lawyer Poets''<ref name=\"lawlit.net\">{{cite web|url=http://lawlit.net/lp-2001/intro/world.html|title=World--Lawyer Poets|website=Lawlit.net|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n*Biographical listing in ABC Bookworld, a reference site for BC literature and authors<ref> http://abcbooksworld.com/writer/22170/ Retrieved on April 14, 2020.</ref>\n*Featured online in ''The Globe and Mail''<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/kudos-to-fern-g-z-carr-poet-lawyer/article621140/|title=Kudos to Fern G. Z. Carr, poet lawyer|accessdate=6 January 2019|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n*Cited as a contributor to India's [[Prakalpana Movement]] \n*Poetry air-dropped in Cyprus in conjunction with ''Spring Poetry Rain''\n*Featured poet (\"Lumi\u00e8re sur\") ''Sipay Revue Litt\u00e9raire Seychelloise'' Num\u00e9ro 12<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sipayrevue.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/sipay-121.pdf|format=PDF|title=SIPAY|edition=12th|website=Sipayrevue.files.wordpress.com|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n*Former League of Canadian Poets' Poet in Residence mentoring young writers\n*Invited to do poetry readings in Mandarin for Chinese New Year 2020 and Spring Lantern Festival 2020\n*Volunteer spotlight for her work in the promotion of literacy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.castanet.net/news/Get-Involved/169945/Get-Volinspired|title=Get Volinspired! - Get Involved|website=Castanet.net|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n*A winner of the Great Canadian Haiku Contest with Carr's poems set to music and performed by [[Juno Award]]-nominated musician [[Royal Wood]]\n*''Shards of Crystal'' selected as Poetry Super Highway Bookstore ''Poets of the Week Featured Book''\n*One of three Canadian adjudicators for the Manitoba Writers' Guild Lansdowne Prize for Poetry / Prix Lansdowne de po\u00e9sie (formerly [[Aqua Books Lansdowne Prize for Poetry]])\n*Western Canadian Judge - ''Ford & Jaguar Automotive Journalist of the Year Awards'' (for two consecutive years)\n*Winner of multiple contests and awards\n\n==Interviews and articles==\n[[Goodreads]] posted an Ask the Author series of questions to Fern G. Z. Carr. Topics included: source of ideas for her book, inspiration, current projects, advice for aspiring writers, the best thing about being a writer and dealing with writer's block.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/7048142.Fern_G_Z_Carr/questions|title=Fern G.Z. Carr answers your questions \u2014 Ask the Author|website=Goodreads.com|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThomas Whyte curates a series of interviews with poets entitled ''poetry mini interviews''. Fern G. Z. Carr was chosen to be one of these featured poets. She was the subject of a series of six weekly interviews to discuss her thoughts about poetry and her work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://poetryminiinterviews.blogspot.com/search/label/Fern%2BG.%2BZ.%2BCarr|title=poetry mini interviews|website=Poetryminiiterviews.blogspot.com|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Kelowna Now - In Focus'' did an extensive feature interview about Carr's life, writing career and achievements.<ref>https://www.kelownanow.com/good_stuff/good_people/news/In_Focus/In_Focus_Fern_G_Z_Carr/#fs_74066. Retrieved on May 11, 2019</ref>\n\n[[CBC Radio One]] (Canadian Broadcast Corporation) host Sarah Penton invited Carr to do a special guest segment on her Radio West show. <ref>https://www.cbc.ca/listen/live-radio/1-96-radio-west (Select airdate Feb 25 2020) Retrieved on April 14 2020.</ref>\n\nUniversity of Winnipeg - ''P.I. New Poetry'' on CKUW 95.9 FM.\n\n''Whole Terrain'', the environmental literary journal of Antioch University (Keene, NH, USA) featured an author profile with Carr. The poet was questioned as to her reflective environmental practices and how they related to her poetry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wholeterrain.com/metamorphosis-author-profile-fern-g-z-carr/|title=Metamorphosis author profile: Fern G.Z. Carr|date=10 October 2017|website=Wholeterrain.com|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nPoet, Marissa Bell Toffoli, interviewed Fern G. Z. Carr on ''Words with Writers W\u00b3 Sidecar''. She interviewed Carr about her poetry writing and revision practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w3sidecar.tumblr.com/post/54685737265/fern-gz-carr|title=Q&A With Writer Fern G Z Carr|website=3sidecar.tumblr.com|accessdate=January 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRyerson University's (Toronto ON, Canada) online newspaper, ''The Eye Opener'', published an article entitled \"Beyond the White Wall.\" It included references to Carr's multiple contributions to their journal, ''The White Wall Review.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theeyeopener.com/2011/10/behind-the-white-wall/|title=Behind the White Wall|website=The Eyeopener|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent to Carr having been included in a database project<ref name=\"lawlit.net\"/> in conjunction with research conducted by West Virginia University law professor, Dr. James R. Elkins, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' featured Fern G. Z. Carr in their online arts section.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ferngzcarr.com Fern G. Z. Carr website]\n*[https://www.pw.org/directory/writers/fern_g_z_carr Poets & Writers]\n*[http://www.poets.ca/directory/ The League of Canadian Poets]\n*[https://www.bcwriters.ca/member-directory/ The Federation of BC Writers]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carr, Fern G.Z.}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kelowna]]\n[[Category:Writers from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Writers from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Canadian women poets]]\n[[Category:University of Manitoba alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Fern G. Z. Carr\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = File:Fern G Z Carr.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth year and age|1956}}\n| birth_place      = [[Winnipeg, Manitoba]], Canada\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Poet, translator, teacher, lawyer\n| language         = English, French, Spanish, Yiddish, Italian, Mandarin\n| residence        = \n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = [[University of Manitoba]];<br>[[Coll\u00e8ge Universitaire de Saint-Boniface]]\n| home_town        = \n| period           = 1978 - present\n| genre            = Poetry\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = Shards of Crystal; I Am\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = Going to Mars with MAVEN; Poem of the Month for Canada\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = {{url|ferngzcarr.com}}\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n\n'''Fern G. Z. Carr''' is a contemporary Canadian poet who resides in [[Kelowna]], [[British Columbia]]. A full member of the League of Canadian Poets and the Federation of BC Writers, Fern G. Z. Carr is the author of ''Shards of Crystal'' (Silver Bow Publishing, 2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.ca/dp/1927616964/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1542292047&sr=8-1&keywords=Shards+of+Crystal+Fern+G.+Z.+Carr|title=Shards of Crystal: Amazon.ca: Fern G. Z. Carr: Books|website=Amazon.ca|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref> Carr is a former lawyer, teacher, and past president of both the Kelowna branch of the BC Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals ([[SPCA]]) and Project Literacy Central Okanagan Society. She composes and translates poetry in six languages including Mandarin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ferngzcarr.com/|title=Fern G. Z. Carr|website=Ferngzcarr.com|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref> She has been published in poetry anthologies, journals, and magazines multiple times in thirty-four countries. One of her poems is currently orbiting the planet [[Mars]] aboard NASA's MAVEN spacecraft. <ref>http://lasp.colorado.edu/home/maven/2013/07/15/public-voting-opens-on-maven-haiku-contest. Retrieved on May 22, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Personal life and education==\nFern G. Z. Carr was born in 1956 in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]]. Carr attended the [[University of Manitoba]] where she obtained her Bachelor of Arts degree (BA) and her Bachelor of Laws degree (LLB). She received her Call to the Bar from the [[Law Society of Manitoba]]. After briefly practising law, Carr decided to pursue her interest in languages. She enrolled at le Coll\u00e8ge Universitaire de Saint-Boniface where she received her Certificat en \u00c9ducation and was the recipient of the Manitoba Government Book Prize for highest standing in her program.<ref>{{cite book |title=The University of Manitoba 104th Annual Convocation |date=1983}}</ref> She subsequently taught French Immersion before moving to [[Kelowna]] with her family in 1999. She is married and is the sister-in-law of [[James Gordon Carr]], Member of Parliament.\n\n==Writing style and influences==\nCarr's early poetry from the late 1970s to the mid-1990s is more representative of traditional meter and rhyme. She subsequently began to experiment with different forms and styles while continuing to compose traditional poetry in set forms such as [[pantoum]] and [[ghazal]]. An admirer of [[Emily Dickinson]], Carr liked the use of [[em dashes]] and often incorporated them into her poems. In the 2000s, Carr's poetry style became more eclectic as she experimented with design. This was particularly evident in her [[Visual poetry|visual]] and [[concrete poetry]] as well as in her experimental math / science poems such as \"The Fickle Nature of the Parabola\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carr |first1=Fern G. Z. |title=The Fickle Nature of the Parabola |journal=Windsor Review |date=Fall 2018 |volume=43 |issue=2 |page=128}}</ref> and \"Holocaust Genealogy\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Carr |first1=Fern G. Z. |title=Holocaust Genealogy |journal=mgversion2 |date=July 2016 |volume=85 |page=84}}</ref> To date, her stylistic focus is [[free verse]].\n\nWhile Carr's poetry primarily is written in English, she also composes poems in [[French language|French]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Yiddish]] and the [[Chinese Mandarin]] dialect. Even though she occasionally translates the works of other poets, she tends to focus on bilingual and trilingual side-by-side translations of her own poetry.\n\nMany of Carr's poems were influenced by her early years in Winnipeg's West End where she bore witness to poverty and crime. While this darkness is evident in some of her poetry, she also composes poems which evoke a diverse array of human emotions.\n\n==''Shards of Crystal''==\n''Shards of Crystal'' reflects a dichotomy and as such, is described as a metamorphosis of darkness to light. Dealing with issues such as suicide, trauma, dementia, cruelty to animals, and the death of a child, the book then gradually changes course. It begins its transformative move towards the beauty of life with poems about musicality, spiritual liberation and the philosophy of existence. It culminates in a philosophical examination of mankind's place in the universe with Carr's signature poem, \"I Am\".<ref name=\"parl.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://bdp.parl.ca/About/Parliament/Poet/poem-selected-former-poet-laureate2-e.html?id=1&id4=254|title=The Parliamentary Poet Laureate|website=Bdp.parl.ca|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe imagery in ''Shards of Crystal'' parallels the darkness-to-light chronology of Carr's poems. This transition is essentially a redemptive move both literally and metaphorically, reconciling the pain of \"Shards\" at the outset of the book with the beauty and enlightenment of \"Crystal\" at the conclusion. Beginning with the darkness of night and becoming progressively lighter, her poems ultimately achieve the illumination of the eternal. This is in keeping with the overarching theme of hope as expressed by the Victor Hugo quote at the start of the book: \"Even the darkest night will end and the sun will rise.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hugo |first1=Victor |title=Les Mis\u00e9rables |date=1987 |publisher=Signet Classics |isbn=9780451525260 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lesmisrablessign00vict }}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nCarr has been published extensively worldwide in Australia, Austria, Canada, China, Cyprus, Finland, France, Holland, India, Ireland, Israel, Italy, Malawi, Mauritius, Mayotte Island, Mexico, Morocco, Nepal, New Zealand, Nigeria, Peru, Philippines, Romania, Seychelles, Singapore, South Africa, Spain, Sweden, Thailand, United Arab Emirates, United Kingdom (in England, Scotland and Wales) and USA.\n\nAdditionally, she has written literary non-fiction articles which have been published in the Federation of BC Writers ''WordWorks Magazine'' (2020) and ''Part of the Discourse: An Interdisciplinary Humanities Journal'' (2019).\n\n===Books===\n*''Shards of Crystal'' (Silver Bow Publishing, 2018) {{ISBN|978-1-927616-96-3}}\n\n===Selected anthologies===\n*''Dreamscapes'' - 2019\n*''Lost and Found'' - 2019\n*''Celestial Musings'' - 2018\n*''Climate of Opinion'' - 2017\n*''Nuclear Impact: Broken Atoms in Our Hands'' - 2017\n*''Fire and Sky'' - 2016\n*''Memory and Loss'' - 2016\n*''Childhood Regained'' - 2016\n*''Amsterdam Quarterly 2015 Yearbook'' - 2015\n*''Contemporary Poetry - An Anthology of Present Day Best Poems'' Vol. 2 - 2015\n*''Love Where the Nights are Twice as Long'' - 2015\n*''A Quiet Shelter There'' - 2015\n*''Storm Cycle 2013 - The Best of Kind of a Hurricane Press'' - 2014\n*''The Body Electric'' - 2013\n*''Voices Israel'' - 2012\n*''Sol: English Writing in Mexico'' - 2012\n*''Butterfly Away'' - 2011\n*''Van Gogh's Ear'' 7 - 2010\n\n===Selected journals===\n*''The Laurel Review'' 51.2 - 2018\n*''The London Reader'' - Autumn, 2017\n*''The Caf\u00e9 Review'' 27 - Winter, 2016\n*''Slant'' - Summer, 2015\n*''Pasque Petals'' - Fall 2015\n*''Whole Terrain'' 21 - 2014\n*''Zona de Carga'' No. 6 - August 2014\n*''MaLa - The Chengdu Bookworm Literary Journal'' 3 - June 2013\n*''Legal Studies Forum'' XXXVII, No. 1 - 2013\n*''phati'tude Literary Magazine'' 3, No. 3 - Fall 2011\n*''The Toronto Quarterly'' 8 - Nov. 2011\n*''White Wall Review'' 135 - 2011\n*''new contrast South African Literary Journal'' 38.4, No. 152 - Summer 2010\n*''The Nashwaak Review'' 24-25, No. 1 - Summer/Fall 2010\n*''Prairie Fire'' 31, No. 3 - Fall 2010\n*''Poetry New Zealand'' 41 - September 2010\n*''Windsor Review'' 42, No. - 2009\n\n==Selected awards and honours==\n*Haiku included on the Going to Mars Contest DVD aboard NASA's MAVEN spacecraft to the planet Mars<ref>http://lasp.colorado.edu/home/maven/2013/07/15/public-voting-opens-on-maven-haiku-contest/. Retrieved on May 22, 2019.</ref>\n*2013 Pushcart Prize Nominee - ''The Worcester Review''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theworcesterreview.org/2013/11/pushcart-nominees.html|title=Pushcart Nominees|first=Diane Vanaskie|last=Mulligan|website=Theworcesterreview.org|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n*A winner of Il Premio Nazionale di Letteratura \"Il Meleteo di Guido Gozzano\" 4\u00b0 Edizione (Sezione Autori di Lingua Straniera)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amicidiguidogozzano.jimdo.com/2014-bando-concorso-e-premiazione/poems-2014/|title=Poems 2014 by country (selected by the judges)|website=Benvenuti su amicidiguidogozzano!|accessdate=25 December 2018}}</ref>\n*Poem, \"I Am\", selected by the Parliamentary Poet Laureate of Canada as Poem of the Month for Canada, May 2010<ref name=\"parl.ca\"/>\n*Featured solo guest presenter at the Rotary Centre for the Arts Mary Irwin Theatre in conjunction with Culture Days and the Kelowna Arts and Culture Festival 2019 <ref>https://www.kelownadailycourier.ca/calendar/event_fc8e2048-bae3-11e9-a845-5cb9017beffc.html. Retrieved on 6 October 2019.</ref>\n*Biographical listing in ''The World's Lawyer Poets''<ref name=\"lawlit.net\">{{cite web|url=http://lawlit.net/lp-2001/intro/world.html|title=World--Lawyer Poets|website=Lawlit.net|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n*Biographical listing in ABC Bookworld, a reference site for BC literature and authors<ref> http://abcbooksworld.com/writer/22170/ Retrieved on April 14, 2020.</ref>\n*Featured online in ''The Globe and Mail''<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/kudos-to-fern-g-z-carr-poet-lawyer/article621140/|title=Kudos to Fern G. Z. Carr, poet lawyer|accessdate=6 January 2019|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n*Cited as a contributor to India's [[Prakalpana Movement]] \n*Poetry air-dropped in Cyprus in conjunction with ''Spring Poetry Rain''\n*Featured poet (\"Lumi\u00e8re sur\") ''Sipay Revue Litt\u00e9raire Seychelloise'' Num\u00e9ro 12<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sipayrevue.files.wordpress.com/2016/01/sipay-121.pdf|format=PDF|title=SIPAY|edition=12th|website=Sipayrevue.files.wordpress.com|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n*Former League of Canadian Poets' Poet in Residence mentoring young writers\n*Invited to do poetry readings in Mandarin for Chinese New Year 2020 and Spring Lantern Festival 2020\n*Volunteer spotlight for her work in the promotion of literacy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.castanet.net/news/Get-Involved/169945/Get-Volinspired|title=Get Volinspired! - Get Involved|website=Castanet.net|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n*A winner of the Great Canadian Haiku Contest with Carr's poems set to music and performed by [[Juno Award]]-nominated musician [[Royal Wood]]\n*''Shards of Crystal'' selected as Poetry Super Highway Bookstore ''Poets of the Week Featured Book''\n*One of three Canadian adjudicators for the Manitoba Writers' Guild Lansdowne Prize for Poetry / Prix Lansdowne de po\u00e9sie (formerly [[Aqua Books Lansdowne Prize for Poetry]])\n*Western Canadian Judge - ''Ford & Jaguar Automotive Journalist of the Year Awards'' (for two consecutive years)\n*Winner of multiple contests and awards\n\n==Interviews and articles==\n[[Goodreads]] posted an Ask the Author series of questions to Fern G. Z. Carr. Topics included: source of ideas for her book, inspiration, current projects, advice for aspiring writers, the best thing about being a writer and dealing with writer's block.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/7048142.Fern_G_Z_Carr/questions|title=Fern G.Z. Carr answers your questions \u2014 Ask the Author|website=Goodreads.com|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nThomas Whyte curates a series of interviews with poets entitled ''poetry mini interviews''. Fern G. Z. Carr was chosen to be one of these featured poets. She was the subject of a series of six weekly interviews to discuss her thoughts about poetry and her work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://poetryminiinterviews.blogspot.com/search/label/Fern%2BG.%2BZ.%2BCarr|title=poetry mini interviews|website=Poetryminiiterviews.blogspot.com|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Kelowna Now - In Focus'' did an extensive feature interview about Carr's life, writing career and achievements.<ref>https://www.kelownanow.com/good_stuff/good_people/news/In_Focus/In_Focus_Fern_G_Z_Carr/#fs_74066. Retrieved on May 11, 2019</ref>\n\nUniversity of Winnipeg - ''P.I. New Poetry'' on CKUW 95.9 FM.\n\n''Whole Terrain'', the environmental literary journal of Antioch University (Keene, NH, USA) featured an author profile with Carr. The poet was questioned as to her reflective environmental practices and how they related to her poetry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wholeterrain.com/metamorphosis-author-profile-fern-g-z-carr/|title=Metamorphosis author profile: Fern G.Z. Carr|date=10 October 2017|website=Wholeterrain.com|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nPoet, Marissa Bell Toffoli, interviewed Fern G. Z. Carr on ''Words with Writers W\u00b3 Sidecar''. She interviewed Carr about her poetry writing and revision practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://w3sidecar.tumblr.com/post/54685737265/fern-gz-carr|title=Q&A With Writer Fern G Z Carr|website=3sidecar.tumblr.com|accessdate=January 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRyerson University's (Toronto ON, Canada) online newspaper, ''The Eye Opener'', published an article entitled \"Beyond the White Wall.\" It included references to Carr's multiple contributions to their journal, ''The White Wall Review.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theeyeopener.com/2011/10/behind-the-white-wall/|title=Behind the White Wall|website=The Eyeopener|accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent to Carr having been included in a database project<ref name=\"lawlit.net\"/> in conjunction with research conducted by West Virginia University law professor, Dr. James R. Elkins, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' featured Fern G. Z. Carr in their online arts section.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ferngzcarr.com Fern G. Z. Carr website]\n*[https://www.pw.org/directory/writers/fern_g_z_carr Poets & Writers]\n*[http://www.poets.ca/directory/ The League of Canadian Poets]\n*[https://www.bcwriters.ca/member-directory/ The Federation of BC Writers]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carr, Fern G.Z.}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kelowna]]\n[[Category:Writers from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Writers from Winnipeg]]\n[[Category:Canadian women poets]]\n[[Category:University of Manitoba alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women]]\n", "name_user": "Bomb319", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInterviews and articles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fern_G._Z._Carr"}
{"title_page": "South Island robin", "text_new": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species),<ref name=Miller>{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref> and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=PowleslandA>{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=Miller/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref name=Gill>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=Worthy>{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=Borkin>{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=Borkin/><ref name=TaylorJamiesonWallis>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref>   There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=IUCN/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=Laws>{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=Hale>{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=Borkin/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=Steffens>{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=PowleslandB/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=SteerBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=PowleslandB/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities. Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs, with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=BoultonPowlesland>{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=Worthy/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=PowleslandB>{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=HuntBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=PowleslandB/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion; however, these are not cached.<ref name=Worthy/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=PowleslandA/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=Barnett>{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators, such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=Hale></ref> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=Hale/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations,<ref name=TaylorJamiesonWallis></ref> although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=Taylor>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Passerine species of bird native to New Zealand's South Island}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = South Island robin\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=IUCN>BirdLife International 2016. Petroica australis. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species 2016: e.T103734942A93987322. https://doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T103734942A93987322.en. Downloaded on 19 August 2019.</ref>\n| image = 070308 Stewart Island robin on Ulva.jpg\n| genus = Petroica\n| species = australis\n| authority = [[Anders Sparrman|Sparrman]], 1788\n}}\n\nThe '''South Island robin''' (''Petroica australis''), is a [[house sparrow|sparrow]]-sized bird found only in [[New Zealand]], where it has the status of a protected endemic species. The birds are sparsely distributed through the [[South Island, New Zealand|South Island]] and [[Stewart Island/Rakiura]], although the distribution is not continuous. The nominate, and the Stewart Island robin (''P. australis rakiura'') are the two [[subspecies]]. The species is closely related to the [[North Island robin]] (formerly ''P. australis longipes'', now considered a distinct species),<ref name=Miller>{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Hilary C.|last2=Lambert|first2=David M.|year=2006|title=A molecular phylogeny of New Zealand's Petroica (Aves: Petroicidae) species based on mitochondrial DNA sequences|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=40|issue=3|pages=844\u2013855|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2006.04.012|pmid=16750641}}</ref> and also to the extremely rare [[black robin]] (''P. traversi'') of the [[Chatham Islands]].\n\n==Description==\n\nThe South Island robin is a small passerine, 10\u201318&nbsp;cm in length and weighing around 35 g. North Island robins do resemble both females and juveniles of the South Island robins, as well as all the Stewart Island robins, which can sometimes make it difficult to distinguish between the three. The females and juveniles within a particular group of robins look similar to each other, although newly independent juveniles may not yet have the more lightly coloured breast patch.<ref name=PowleslandA>{{cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1997|title=Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins: Petroica australis|series=Department of Conservation Technical Series|volume=13|publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation}}</ref> However, male North Island robins are almost black with a white spot just above the beak, as well as the greyish-white lower breast. Females and juveniles are greyer with more variable pale patches on their breasts and throats. Male South Island robins are dark grey, except for the distinct yellowish-white lower chest, while females and juveniles are again lighter grey with a less distinct breast. Finally, Stewart Island robins look similar to North Island robins (both males and females).<ref name=IUCN/>\n\nNew Zealand robins are relatively long-lived; life-spans of at least 14 years have been recorded in the wild.\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:New Zealand Robin.jpg|thumb|left|South Island robin]]\nThe South Island robin has two subspecies: ''P. australis australis'', the nominate form, and ''P. australis rakiura'', the Stewart Island robin. These subspecies do not overlap in their distributions. The [[North Island robin]] (''P. longipes''), the [[tomtit]] (''Petroica macrocephala''), and the [[black robin]] (''Petroica traversi'') in the Chatham Islands are closely related species. ''P. traversi'' seems to be a Chatham Island derivative of ''P. australis'', although the position of the most recent common ancestor has yet to be determined.<ref name=Miller/> The family [[Petroicidae]] of Australasian robins has a total of 49 species, mostly in Australia, [[New Zealand]], and [[New Guinea]].<ref name=Gill>Gill, F. and D. Donsker, eds. (2020). IOC World Bird List (v 10.1). Doi 10.14344/IOC.ML.10.1.  http://www.worldbirdnames.org/</ref>.\n\n==Fossil record==\nThere is molecular phylogenetic evidence to suggest two waves of immigration by the Petroica genus from Australia. ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' can be traced to the first and ''P. macrocephala'' to the second wave. The evidence suggests that ''P. longipes'' and ''P. australis'' began to diverge prior to the [[Pleistocene]] era, and that the two South Island subspecies of ''P. australis'' began to diverge after the [[Pleistocene]] era. The separation time for the former was about three million years, and only 10,000 years (i.e., postglacial) for the latter. Fossils of New Zealand robins can sometimes be found near pit fall deposits, as they do most of their feeding/foraging on the ground.<ref name=Worthy>{{cite book|last1=Worthy|first1=Trevor H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=Richard N.|year=2002|chapter=Shorebirds, Parrots and Passerines|title=The Lost World of the Moa|pages=410\u2013440}}</ref> The fossil record also indicates the robins' presence throughout lowland New Zealand until drastic habitat reduction through deforestation by the [[Polynesians|Polynesian]] ancestors of the [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]] and later European colonisers.<ref name=Borkin>{{cite journal|last=Borkin|first=K. M.|last2=Goodman|first2=A. J.|last3=Mayhew|first3=K.|last4=Smith|first4=E.|year=2007|title=South Island robin (Petroica australis australis) abundance and leaf-litter invertebrates in plantation and native forest|journal=Notornis|volume=54|issue=2|pages=65}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\n[[File:Petroica australis -Southland District, South Island, New Zealand-8.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin, [[Southland District]]]]\nHistorically, the South Island robin inhabited much of the lowland of New Zealand's South Island, but its distribution has become much more patchy in the last century due to habitat loss and introduced predation.<ref name=Borkin/><ref name=TaylorJamiesonWallis>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|last3=Wallis|first3=G. P.|year=2007|title=Historic and contemporary levels of genetic variation in two New Zealand passerines with different histories of decline|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=20|issue=5|pages=2035\u20132047|doi=10.1111/j.1420-9101.2007.01362.x|pmid=17714320}}</ref>   There are two populations on the east coast of the South Island, and they are slightly more common in the north and west.<ref name=IUCN/> It has fared slightly better than the Stewart Island robin, which has been relegated to 3 subpopulations, all of which are in [[Leptospermum]] swamp scrubland\u2014although this is not their preferred habitat, it is less heavily populated by mammalian predators. Total population was lower than 500 individuals at one point.<ref name=Laws>{{cite journal|last1=Laws|first1=R. J.|last2=Jamieson|first2=I. G.|year=2011|title=Is lack of evidence of inbreeding depression in a threatened New Zealand robin indicative of reduced genetic load?|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=14|issue=1|pages=47\u201355|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2010.00388.x}}</ref> A programme of translocation to predator-free islands (such as [[Ulva Island (New Zealand)|Ulva Island]], Motuara Island, and Nukuwaiata Island) has since been instituted that has been relatively successful at establishing new populations (around 600 individuals on Motuara alone).<ref name=Hale>{{cite journal|last1=Hale|first1=K. A.|last2=Briskie|first2=J. V.|year=2007|title=Decreased immunocompetence in a severely bottlenecked population of an endemic New Zealand bird.|journal=Animal Conservation|volume=10|issue=1|pages=2\u201310|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2006.00059.x}}</ref> In the South Island, ''P. australis'' has a strong affinity for [[Douglas fir]] plantations rather than native forests ([[Kunzea ericoides|kanuka]] trees) or [[Monterey pine]] plantations, apparently due to forest structure rather than strict food availability or viable nesting sites, as the species prefers structurally simple forests with dense, even canopies, and ground covered with leaf litter.<ref name=Borkin/> When the population was introduced to Ulva Island, nesting was positively correlated with presence of broad-leaved coastal vegetation.<ref name=Steffens>{{cite journal|last1=Steffens|first1=K. E.|last2=Seddon|first2=P. J.|last3=Mathieu|first3=R.|last4=Jamieson|first4=I. G.|year=2005|title=Habitat selection by South Island saddlebacks and Stewart Island robins reintroduced to Ulva Island|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=2005|pages=221\u2013229}}</ref>\n\n==Behaviour and ecology==\n\n===Breeding===\n\nSouth Island robins are [[Monogamy|genetically monogamous]], and extra-pair paternity is rare. As they do typically remain monogamous, are non-migratory, and remain on their breeding territories year-round, a male and female in one territory will compete for food resources during non-breeding times. Competition is reduced somewhat by slightly different foraging methods; however, they will steal from their mate's cache if given the opportunity.<ref name=PowleslandB/> Males do dominate females, and thus will aggressively exclude females from food, such that females will only access food sources when unattended by the males.<ref name=SteerBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Steer|first1=Jamie|last2=Burns|first2=KC|year=2008|title=Seasonal variation in male-female competition, cooperation and selfish hoarding in a monogamous songbird|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|volume=62|issue=7|pages=1175\u20131183|doi=10.1007/s00265-008-0546-z}}</ref> During breeding season, the female is solely responsible for nest building and incubation, and the male will provide the female and the hatchlings with food.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\nSouth Island robins become sexually mature between six and 12 months of age. They begin their breeding season fairly early in August or September (Southern Hemisphere spring) and thus can make use of the winter's remaining food stores during this time.<ref name=PowleslandB/> They build open-cup nests in tree-forks or inside tree cavities. Incubation lasts 18 days, and chicks leave the nest after 21 days. Five to 25 days after fledglings leave the nest, the pair may breed again. Modal clutch size is two eggs, with the expected inverse correlation between size and number of eggs.<ref name=BoultonPowlesland>{{cite journal|last1=Boulton|first1=Rebecca L|last2=Powlesland|first2=Ralph G.|year=2008|title=Variation in egg size and nest survival with female age in the South Island Robin Petroica australis|journal=Ibis|volume=150|issue=4|pages=824\u2013828|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919x.2008.00853.x}}</ref> Replacement clutches in the case of loss of eggs or nestlings to predation can be produced relatively rapidly, within 3\u201310 days.<ref name=PowleslandA/>\n\n===Feeding===\n[[File:NZ Robin 2008.JPG|thumb|right|Stewart Island robin]]\nInvertebrates, including earthworms, beetles, and other arthropods foraged from the leaf litter comprise most of the South Island robins' diet.<ref name=Worthy/> Invertebrate prey may be [[Hoarding (animal behavior)|cached]] whole or in portions. Single items are cached at separate sites. Prey is typically stored within 10 metres of where it was procured, even if the bird is outside its own territory. In the winter the primary cache is earthworms, while during the summer the trend is toward cicadas. South Island robins have a very good memory of their storage sites; a male was observed to empty as many as five consecutive caches before returning the stores to his mate during incubation.<ref name=PowleslandB>{{cite journal|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.|year=1980|title=Food-Storing Behavior of the South Island Robin|journal=Mauri Ora|volume=8|pages=11}}</ref> The birds have demonstrated an ability to differentiate and prioritise caches of varying sizes, up to 12 total items, without any training, which appears to be the highest recorded numerical competency of any wild animal.<ref name=HuntBurns>{{cite journal|last1=Hunt|first1=Simon|last2=Low|first2=Jason|last3=Burns|first3=K.C.|year=2008|title=Adaptive numerical competency in a food-hoarding songbird|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences|volume=275|issue=1649|pages=2373\u20132379|doi=10.1098/rspb.2008.0702|pmc=2603231|pmid=18611847}}</ref> Because of its high metabolic rate, a robin might spend as much as 90% of its day foraging or storing during the winter.<ref name=PowleslandB/> South Island robins have also been observed to eat berries on occasion; however, these are not cached.<ref name=Worthy/>\n\n===Vocalisation===\n[[File:Southislandrobin.jpg|thumb|right|South Island robin]]\nA male's call during non-breeding season is a series of loud notes with descending frequency which start in rapid succession and finish slowly. During breeding season, the males resort to full song to court the females. Full song is a loud, clear, and continuous song which can last for more than 30 minutes with very brief pauses, and is typically sung from the canopy or an [[Rainforest#Emergent layer|emergent]] tree.<ref name=PowleslandA/> Singing also appears to be performed as part of a strategic regulation of body mass. While robins sing during the [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn chorus]] as well as throughout the day, they seem to increase their singing according to food availability. When they have had more food, they will increase energetic behaviours such as singing to arrive at a strategic mass by dusk. Thus, even though two robins might begin the day with different weights, they will end the day with similar weights. A side effect of this behaviour might be the showcasing of a particular male's ability to sequester resources: the longer he sings, the more capable he is of finding food, and thus a better candidate for a mate.<ref name=Barnett>{{cite journal|last1=Barnett|first1=Craig A.|last2=Briskie|first2=James V.|year=2011|title=Strategic Regulation of Body Mass and Singing Behavior in New Zealand Robins|journal=Ethology|volume=117|issue=1|pages=28\u201336|doi=10.1111/j.1439-0310.2010.01844.x}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nThe South Island robin is listed as being of [[least concern]] on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN/> However, the Stewart Island robin (''Petroica australis rakiura'') has gone through a couple of bottlenecked populations recently because of deforestation and habitat loss, as well as introduced predators, such as rats, stoats, and feral cats.<ref name=Hale></ref> Because of this sharp decline in the Stewart Island population, several attempts have been made to translocate the Stewart Island robin to other islands nearby where introduced predators do not exist or have been eradicated (see [[South Island robin#Distribution|above]]. However, many of these translocations have involved 12 or fewer colonising individuals, making inbreeding nearly unavoidable. This has led to some apparent immunocompetency issues as well as reproduction problems. On Motuara Island high rates of hatching failure as well as fewer clutches were observed.<ref name=Hale/> Inbreeding and its genetic and immunological consequences therefore remain a concern with this subspecies.\n\nIn contrast, birds in the South Island do not show much genetic loss in comparison with historical populations, although their distribution on the island has become increasingly fragmented.<ref name=Taylor>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=S. S.|last2=Boessenkool|first2=S.|last3=Jamieson|first3=I. G.|year=2008|title=Genetic monogamy in two long\u2010lived New Zealand passerines|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=39|issue=5|pages=579\u2013583|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2008.04331.x}}</ref>\n\n==South Island robins and 1080 poison==\n\nA number of robin deaths have been recorded as a result of accidental [[sodium fluoroacetate|1080]] poisoning following pest control operations.<ref name=spurr>{{cite book|last=Spurr|first=E.|year=2000|chapter=Impacts of possum control on non-target species|editor=T.L. Montague|title=The brushtail possum: biology, impact and management of an introduced marsupial|publisher=Manaaki Whenua Press|location=Lincoln}}</ref> Most of these were associated with four specific operations in the 1980s that used poor-quality carrot baits.<ref name=\"pce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests/|title=Evaluating the use of 1080: Predators, poisons and silent forests|date=June 2011|publisher=Parliamentary Commissioner for the Environment|accessdate=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110614233345/http://www.pce.parliament.nz/publications/all-publications/evaluating-the-use-of-1080-predators-poisons-and-silent-forests|archivedate=14 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These instances aside, robins have generally responded well to pest control programmes using aerial 1080 operations, with increased chick and adult survival, and increases in population size.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Powlesland|first1=R. G.|last2=Knegtmans|first2=J. W.|last3=Marshall|first3=I. S. J.|year=1999|title=Costs and benefits of aerial 1080 possum control operations using carrot baits to North Island robins (Petroica australis longipes), Pureora Forest Park|journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|volume=1999|pages=149\u2013159|url=http://www.lincoln.ac.nz/PageFiles/7074/3474_Powleslandetal__s10663.pdf}}</ref> A 2012 scientific study of a [[Bird ringing|marked]] population by the [[University of Otago]] during a contemporary 1080 poison operation using cereal baits showed no negative impact on robins and suggested a likely population increase by reducing predation pressure from introduced mammals.<ref name=\"TVNZ One News\">{{cite news |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/national-news/study-finds-1080-has-positive-effect-bird-population-video-4844337 |title=Study finds 1080 has positive effect on bird population |author=TVNZ |date=22 April 2012 |work=[[TVNZ]] |accessdate=26 April 2012}}</ref><!-- DEAD LINK Schadewinkel et al. |title=The effect of aerial application of 1080 cereal baits for possum control on South Island robin (Petroica australis) in the Silver Peaks, Dunedin'|url=http://tbfree.org.nz/Portals/0/Research/1080%20-%20robin%20report_final-revised.pdf -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/conservation/native-animals/birds/land-birds/nz-robin-toutouwai/ New Zealand Robin] on [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] website\n* [http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/toutouwai.html Factsheet on toutouwai, the New Zealand robin] at NZBirds.com\n* [http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/1966/robin/1/ Information about New Zealand robins] on [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]\n* [http://www.doc.org.nz/upload/documents/science-and-technical/docts13.pdf Protocols for monitoring New Zealand robins(Petroica australis)] - [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] Technical Series No. 13\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bwLBfaX4VjE/ Video footage of New Zealand robins] on the [[Animal Health Board (New Zealand)|Animal Health Board]] YouTube Channel\n\n{{Petroicidae}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Portal bar|Birds|New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1051396}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, South Island}}\n[[Category:Petroica|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the South Island]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1788|South Island robin]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Anders Sparrman]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eConservation:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Island_robin"}
{"title_page": "Ian McHugh", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image        = Ian McHugh.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| name         = Ian McHugh\n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation   = \n| nationality  = [[Australia]]n\n| period       = \n| genre        = [[Speculative fiction|Speculative]] [[short fiction]]\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = '''Aurealis Award'''<br>{{awd|award=[[Aurealis Award for best fantasy short story|Best fantasy short story]]|year=2009|title=\"[[Once a Month, On a Sunday]]\"}}'''Writers of the Future'''<br>{{awd|award=[[Writers of the Future|Grand prize]]|year=2008|title=\"Bitter Dreams\"}}\n| signature    = \n| website      = {{URL|http://ianmchugh.wordpress.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Ian McHugh''' is an [[Australia]]n writer of [[Speculative fiction|speculative]] [[short fiction]].\n\n==Biography==\nMcHugh's first story was published in 2004, entitled \"The Alchemical Automaton Blues\" which was published in ''[[Andromeda Spaceways Inflight Magazine]]'' #15.<ref name=\"ISFDB TAAB\">{{cite web | url = http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?1020444 | title = Bibliography: The Alchemical Automaton Blues | publisher = [[ISFDB]] | date = | accessdate = 2010-03-06}}</ref> His first win came with his story \"Bitter Dreams\" which won the 2008 [[Writers of the Future]] grand prize.<ref name=\"LO INDEX\">{{cite web | url = http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/NomLit89.html#6341-2008 | title = The Locus Index to SF Awards: Index of Literary Nominees: Page 89 | publisher = [[Locus Online]] | accessdate = 2010-03-06 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080308120606/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/NomLit89.html#6341-2008 | archivedate = 2008-03-08 }}</ref> It was also a nominee for the writers of the Future 3rd quarter at the same awards and was a short-list nominee for the 2008 [[Aurealis Award for best horror short story]].<ref name=\"LO INDEX\"/> In 2009 McHugh's \"[[Once a Month, On a Sunday]]\" was a joint-winner for the 2009 [[Aurealis Award for best fantasy short story]].<ref name=\"AA 2009FSJR\">{{cite web|url=http://aurealisawards.com/downloads/FantasyShort.pdf |title=Aurealis Awards 2009 Fantasy Short Story: Judges\u2019 Report |publisher=[[Aurealis Awards]] |accessdate=2010-03-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707185416/http://aurealisawards.com/downloads/FantasyShort.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-07 }}</ref> McHugh currently lives in [[Canberra]], [[Australia]] and is a member of the Canberra Speculative Fiction Guild.<ref name=\"IM A\">{{cite web | url = http://ianmchugh.wordpress.com/about/ | title = About | publisher = ianmchugh.wordpress.com | date = | accessdate = 2010-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=August 2018}}\n\n;Collections\n* Angel dust (2014)\n;Stories<ref>Short stories unless otherwise noted.</ref>\n{|class='wikitable sortable' width='90%'\n|-\n!width=25%|Title\n!|Year\n!|First published\n!|Reprinted/collected\n!|Notes\n|-\n|Extracted journal notes for an ethnography of Bnebene nomad culture\n|2014\n|{{cite journal |author=McHugh, Ian |authormask= |date=Jan 2014 |title=Extracted journal notes for an ethnography of Bnebene nomad culture |department= |journal=Asimov's Science Fiction |volume=38 |issue=1 |pages=30\u201343}}\n| \n|\n|-\n|}\n<!-- Move entries below into the table above -->\n* {{cite journal |author=McHugh, Ian |authormask= |date=2004 |title=The Alchemical Automaton Blues |department= |journal=Andromeda Spaceways Inflight Magazine |volume=15 |issue= |pages=}}\n*\"The Last Day of Rea\" (2006) in ''All Star Stories presents: Twenty Epics''\n*\"Grace\" (2007) in ''[[Andromeda Spaceways Inflight Magazine]]'' #28 (ed. [[Zara Baxter]])\n*\"The Dao of Stones\" (2007) in ''Challenging Destiny'' #24\n*\"Requiem in D-minor (for prions, whale and burning bush)\" (2007) in ''[[Hub (magazine)|Hub]]'' #24\n*\"The Greatest Adventure of All\" (2007) in ''Coyote Wild'', Autumn 2007\n*\"[[Bitter Dreams]]\" (2008) in ''Writers of the Future XXIV'' (ed. [[Algis Budrys]])\n*\"Stiletto\" (2009) in ''[[GUD Magazine|GUD]]'' #4\n*\"Angel Dust\" (2009) in ''Clockwork Phoenix 2''\n*\"Sleepless in the House of Ye\" (2009) in ''[[Asimov's Science Fiction]]'' July 2009 (ed. [[Sheila Williams]])\n*\"[[Once a Month, On a Sunday]]\" (2009) in ''[[Andromeda Spaceways Inflight Magazine]]'' #40\n*\"Songdogs\" (2009) in ''Beneath Ceaseless Skies'' #27\n*\"The Promises of Avalae\" (2010) in ''Blood & Devotion''\n*\"Annicca\" (2010) in ''[[Greatest Uncommon Denominator]]'' #6\n*\"Cockatoo\" (TBA) in ''All Hallows''\n*\"The Godbreaker and Unggubudh the Mountain\" (2012) in ''[[Light Touch Paper, Stand Clear]]'' (ed. Edwina Harvey and [[Simon Petrie]])\n* {{cite journal |author=McHugh, Ian |authormask=1 |date=Oct-Nov 2013 |title=When the rain comin |journal=Asimov's Science Fiction |volume=37 |issue=10-11 |pages=42\u201344}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n'''Aurealis Awards'''<ref name=\"LO INDEX\"/>\n*'''[[Aurealis Award for best fantasy short story|Best fantasy short story]]'''\n*2009: Win: \"[[Once a Month, On a Sunday]]\"\n*'''[[Aurealis Award for best horror short story|Best horror short story]]'''\n*2008: Nomination: \"Bitter Dreams\"\n*'''[[Aurealis Award for best young-adult short story|Best young-adult short story]]'''\n*2009: Win: \"Once a Month, On a Sunday\"\n\n'''Writers of the Future'''<ref name=\"LO INDEX\"/>\n*'''[[Writers of the Future|Writers of the Future grand prize]]'''\n*2008: Win: \"Bitter Dreams\"\n*'''[[Writers of the Future|Writers of the Future 3rd quarter]]'''\n*2008: Nominee: \"Bitter Dreams\"\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://ianmchugh.wordpress.com/ Official site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McHugh, Ian}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Asimov's Science Fiction people]]\n[[Category:Australian fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:Australian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Australian science fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image        = Ian McHugh.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| name         = Ian McHugh\n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| occupation   = \n| nationality  = [[Australia]]n\n| period       = \n| genre        = [[Speculative fiction|Speculative]] [[short fiction]]\n| subject      = \n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = \n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = '''Aurealis Award'''<br>{{awd|award=[[Aurealis Award for best fantasy short story|Best fantasy short story]]|year=2009|title=\"[[Once a Month, On a Sunday]]\"}}'''Writers of the Future'''<br>{{awd|award=[[Writers of the Future|Grand prize]]|year=2008|title=\"Bitter Dreams\"}}\n| signature    = \n| website      = {{URL|http://ianmchugh.wordpress.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Ian McHugh''' is an [[Australia]]n writer of [[Speculative fiction|speculative]] [[short fiction]].\n\n==Biography==\nMcHugh's first story was published in 2004, entitled \"The Alchemical Automaton Blues\" which was published in ''[[Andromeda Spaceways Inflight Magazine]]'' #15.<ref name=\"ISFDB TAAB\">{{cite web | url = http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?1020444 | title = Bibliography: The Alchemical Automaton Blues | publisher = [[ISFDB]] | date = | accessdate = 2010-03-06}}</ref> His first win came with his story \"Bitter Dreams\" which won the 2008 [[Writers of the Future]] grand prize.<ref name=\"LO INDEX\">{{cite web | url = http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/NomLit89.html#6341-2008 | title = The Locus Index to SF Awards: Index of Literary Nominees: Page 89 | publisher = [[Locus Online]] | accessdate = 2010-03-06 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080308120606/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/NomLit89.html#6341-2008 | archivedate = 2008-03-08 }}</ref> It was also a nominee for the writers of the Future 3rd quarter at the same awards and was a short-list nominee for the 2008 [[Aurealis Award for best horror short story]].<ref name=\"LO INDEX\"/> In 2009 McHugh's \"[[Once a Month, On a Sunday]]\" was a joint-winner for the 2009 [[Aurealis Award for best fantasy short story]].<ref name=\"AA 2009FSJR\">{{cite web|url=http://aurealisawards.com/downloads/FantasyShort.pdf |title=Aurealis Awards 2009 Fantasy Short Story: Judges\u2019 Report |publisher=[[Aurealis Awards]] |accessdate=2010-03-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707185416/http://aurealisawards.com/downloads/FantasyShort.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-07 }}</ref> McHugh currently lives in [[Canberra]], [[Australia]] and is a member of the Canberra Speculative Fiction Guild.<ref name=\"IM A\">{{cite web | url = http://ianmchugh.wordpress.com/about/ | title = About | publisher = ianmchugh.wordpress.com | date = | accessdate = 2010-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Expand list|date=August 2018}}\n\n;Collections\n* Angel dust (2014)\n;Stories<ref>Short stories unless otherwise noted.</ref>\n{|class='wikitable sortable' width='90%'\n|-\n!width=25%|Title\n!|Year\n!|First published\n!|Reprinted/collected\n!|Notes\n|-\n|Extracted journal notes for an ethnography of Bnebene nomad culture\n|2014\n|{{cite journal |author=McHugh, Ian |authormask= |date=Jan 2014 |title=Extracted journal notes for an ethnography of Bnebene nomad culture |department= |journal=Asimov's Science Fiction |volume=38 |issue=1 |pages=30\u201343}}\n| \n|\n|-\n|}\n<!-- Move entries below into the tab